{"id":14881442,"mediaExerciseId":"2c59d7bb-a52b-40c0-9678-c9e08fdef38d","exerciseName":"7","chapterName":"14","chapterTitle":"Cost of Capital","groupId":null,"groupTitle":null,"isPremium":true,"sectionName":"14.7","sectionTitle":"Flotation Costs and the Average Cost of Capital","pageNumber":485,"solutions":[{"id":5980061,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"$a)$ When a corporation issues stocks and bonds for only a new project, then the cost of floating is incurred, it's really the additional expenditure that is factored into the firm's overall capital demand.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":105,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/03/f4bb918c49c010a641d6e4743e92b05b/1d1d720f1fe9fdbc1595db0ce79b1205/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":53,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/03/f4bb918c49c010a641d6e4743e92b05b/1d1d720f1fe9fdbc1595db0ce79b1205/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"\n$b)$ The extra expense spent while investing in a project is known as the flotation cost, it is required to modify this cost as a cash outflow for the firm when calculating the net present value in this case, whenever the net present value is calculated without taking into account the cost of floatation, the outcome is not believed to be the genuine net present value, just after correcting the flotation cost can the genuine net present value be calculated.\n\n Therefore, there is a probability that the project's net present value will be positive even if the flotation cost is not included in the issuance cost, however, after accounting for the flotation cost, which includes issuance costs and finance arrangements, the net present value may be negative, indicating that the company should not proceed with the project.\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":406,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/03/f4bb918c49c010a641d6e4743e92b05b/bd90b6dfecc4a76c9ee534203d28ee28/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":204,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/03/f4bb918c49c010a641d6e4743e92b05b/bd90b6dfecc4a76c9ee534203d28ee28/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"0eb5f0f0-552a-4829-8c54-d5a7ebcb132a","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":2}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","edition":"12th Edition","verifiedSolutionCount":1217,"shouldBeIndexableForSeo":true,"modified":1665448474394,"active":true,"publisher":"McGraw-Hill Education","mainTextbookIsbn":null,"subjects":{"level1":["Social Science"],"level2":["Economics"],"level3":["Finance"]}},"nextExercises":[{"id":14881443,"exerciseName":"1","page":487,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"7a668045-9f58-4331-a53f-49856fd95c02","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-14-exercises-1-7a668045-9f58-4331-a53f-49856fd95c02"},{"id":14881444,"exerciseName":"2","page":487,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"d11e0efb-c919-4df5-a6ac-1631728dadbd","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-14-exercises-2-d11e0efb-c919-4df5-a6ac-1631728dadbd"}],"previousExercises":[{"id":14881441,"exerciseName":"6","page":482,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"5fad7f16-1b87-4abb-9b3b-7b29c7e70b7e","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/expl